# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flowering-plant
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The **ABC model of flower development** is a scientific model of the process by which flowering plants produce a pattern of gene expression in meristems that leads to the appearance of an organ oriented towards sexual reproduction, a flower.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The latter phase has been modelled using the **ABC model**, which aims to describe the biological basis of the process from the perspective of molecular and developmental genetics.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] An external stimulus is required in order to trigger the differentiation of the meristem into a flower meristem.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This stimulus will activate mitotic cell division in the apical meristem, particularly on its sides where new primordia are formed.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This same stimulus will also cause the meristem to follow a developmental pattern that will lead to the growth of floral meristems as opposed to vegetative meristems.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The main difference between these two types of meristem, apart from the obvious disparity between the objective organ, is the verticillate (or whorled) phyllotaxis, that is, the absence of stem elongation among the successive whorls or verticils of the primordium.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] These verticils follow an acropetal development, giving rise to sepals, petals, stamens and carpels.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Another difference from vegetative axillary meristems is that the floral meristem is "determined", which means that, once differentiated, its cells will no longer divide.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The identity of the organs present in the four floral verticils is a consequence of the interaction of at least three types of gene products, each with distinct functions.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] According to the ABC model, functions A and C are required in order to determine the identity of the verticils of the perianth and the reproductive verticils, respectively.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] These functions are exclusive and the absence of one of them means that the other will determine the identity of all the floral verticils.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B function allows the differentiation of petals from sepals in the secondary verticil, as well as the differentiation of the stamen from the carpel on the tertiary verticil.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Goethe's **foliar theory** was formulated in the 18th century and it suggests that the constituent parts of a flower are structurally modified leaves, which are functionally specialized for reproduction or protection.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The transition from the vegetative phase to a reproductive phase involves a dramatic change in the plant's vital cycle, perhaps the most important one, as the process must be carried out correctly in order to guarantee that the plant produces descendants.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This transition is characterised by the induction and development of the meristem of the inflorescence, which will produce a collection of flowers or one flower.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This morphogenetic change contains both endogenous and exogenous elements: For example, in order for the change to be initiated the plant must have a certain number of leaves and contain a certain level of total biomass.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Certain environmental conditions are also required such as a characteristic photoperiod.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Plant hormones play an important part in the process, with the gibberellins having a particularly important role.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are many signals that regulate the molecular biology of the process.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The following three genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana* possess both common and independent functions in floral transition: *FLOWERING LOCUS T* (*FT*), *LEAFY* (*LFY*), *SUPPRESSOR OF OVEREXPRESSION OF CONSTANS1* (*SOC1*, also called *AGAMOUS-LIKE20*).
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] *SOC1* is a MADS-box-type gene, which integrates responses to photoperiod, vernalization and gibberellins.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The meristem can be defined as the tissue or group of plant tissues that contain undifferentiated stem cells, which are capable of producing any type of cell tissue.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Their maintenance and development, both in the vegetative meristem or the meristem of the inflorescence is controlled by genetic cell fate determination mechanisms.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that a number of genes will directly regulate, for example, the maintenance of the stem cell's characteristics (gene *WUSCHEL* or *WUS*), and others will act via negative feedback mechanisms in order to inhibit a characteristic (gene *CLAVATA* or *CLV*).
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this way both mechanisms give rise to a feedback loop, which along with other elements lend a great deal of robustness to the system.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Along with the *WUS* gene the *SHOOTMERISTEMLESS* (*STM*) gene also represses the differentiation of the meristematic dome.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This gene acts by inhibiting the possible differentiation of the stem cells but still allows cell division in the daughter cells, which, had they been allowed to differentiate, would have given rise to distinct organs.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] A flower's anatomy, as defined by the presence of a series of organs (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels) positioned according to a given pattern, facilitate sexual reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model of flower development was first formulated by George Haughn and Chris Somerville in 1988.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was first used as a model to describe the collection of genetic mechanisms that establish floral organ identity in the Rosids, as exemplified by *Arabidopsis thaliana*, and the Asterids, as demonstrated by *Antirrhinum majus*.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both species have four verticils (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels), which are defined by the differential expression of a number of homeotic genes present in each verticil.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that the sepals are solely characterized by the expression of A genes, while the petals are characterized by the co-expression of A and B genes.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B and C genes establish the identity of the stamens and the carpels only require C genes to be active.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Type A and C genes are reciprocally antagonistic.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The fact that these homeotic genes determine an organ's identity becomes evident when a gene that represents a particular function, for example the A gene, is not expressed.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* this loss results in a flower which is composed of one verticil of carpels, another containing stamens and another of carpels.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This method for studying gene function uses reverse genetics techniques to produce transgenic plants that contain a mechanism for gene silencing through RNA interference.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In other studies, using forward genetics techniques such as genetic mapping, it is the analysis of the phenotypes of flowers with structural anomalies that leads to the cloning of the gene of interest.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The flowers may possess a non-functional or over expressed allele for the gene being studied.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The existence of two supplementary functions, D and E, have also been proposed in addition to the A, B and C functions already discussed.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function D specifies the identity of the ovule, as a separate reproductive function from the development of the carpels, which occurs after their determination.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function E relates to a physiological requirement that is a characteristic of all floral verticils, although, it was initially described as necessary for the development of the three innermost verticils (Function E *sensu stricto*).
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, its broader definition (*sensu lato*) suggests that it is required in the four verticils.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The gene products of genes with D and E functions are also MADS-box genes.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The methodology for studying flower development involves two steps.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Firstly, the identification of the exact genes required for determining the identity of the floral meristem.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* these include APETALA1 (*AP1*) and LEAFY (*LFY*).
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Secondly, genetic analysis is carried out on the aberrant phenotypes for the relative characteristics of the flowers, which allows the characterization of the homeotic genes implicated in the process.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are a great many mutations that affect floral morphology, although the analysis of these mutants is a recent development.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Supporting evidence for the existence of these mutations comes from the fact that a large number affect the identity of floral organs.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] For example, some organs develop in a location where others should develop.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is called homeotic mutation, which is analogous to HOX gene mutations found in *Drosophila*.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* and *Antirrhinum*, the two taxa on which models are based, these mutations always affect adjacent verticils.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Cloning studies have been carried out on DNA in the genes associated with the affected homeotic functions in the mutants discussed above.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] These studies used serial analysis of gene expression throughout floral development to show patterns of tissue expression, which, in general, correspond with the predictions of the ABC model.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The nature of these genes corresponds to that of transcription factors, which, as expected, have analogous structures to a group of factors contained in yeasts and animal cells.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This group is called MADS, which is an acronym for the different factors contained in the group.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] These MADS factors have been detected in all the vegetable species studied, although the involvement of other elements involved in the regulation of gene expression cannot be discounted.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, function A is mainly represented by two genes *APETALA1* (*AP1)* and *APETALA2* (*AP2*) *AP1* is a MADS-box type gene, while *AP2* belongs to the family of genes that contains AP2, which it gives its name to and which consists of transcription factors that are only found in plants.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] AP2 has also been shown to complex with the co-repressor TOPLESS (TPL) in developing floral buds to repress the C-class gene *AGAMOUS* (*AG*).
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] *AP2* not only functions in the first two verticils, but also in the remaining two, in developing ovules and even in leaves.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] It is also likely that post-transcriptional regulation exists, which controls its A function, or even that it has other purposes in the determination of organ identity independent of that mentioned here.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Antirrhinum*, the orthologous gene to *AP1* is *SQUAMOSA* (*SQUA*), which also has a particular impact on the floral meristem.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs for *AP2* are *LIPLESS1* (*LIP1*) and *LIPLESS2* (*LIP2*), which have a redundant function and are of special interest in the development of sepals, petals and ovules.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] A total of three genes have been isolated from *Petunia hybrida* that are similar to *AP2*: *P. hybrida APETALA2A* (*PhAP2A*), *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] *PhAP2A* is, to a large degree, homologous with the *AP2* gene of *Arabidopsis*, both in its sequence and in its expression pattern, which suggests that the two genes are orthologs.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The proteins *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*, on the other hand, are slightly different, even though they belong to the family of transcription factors that are similar to *AP2*.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition they are expressed in different ways, although they are very similar in comparison with *PhAP2A*.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In fact, the mutants for these genes do not show the usual phenotype, that of the null alleles of A genes.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* the type-B function mainly arises from two genes, *APETALA3* (*AP3*) and *PISTILLATA* (*PI*), both of which are MADS-box genes.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] A mutation of either of these genes causes the homeotic conversion of petals into sepals and of stamens into carpels.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This also occurs in its orthologs in *A. majus*, which are DEFICIENS (*DEF*) and *GLOBOSA* (*GLO*) respectively.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] For both species the active form of binding with DNA is that derived from the heterodimer: AP3 and PI, or DEF and GLO, dimerize.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is the form in which they are able to function.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *GLO*/*PI* lines that have been duplicated in *Petunia* contain *P. hybrida GLOBOSA1* (*PhGLO1*, also called *FBP1*) and also *PhGLO2* (also called *PMADS2* or *FBP3*).
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] For the functional elements equivalent to *AP3*/*DEF* in *Petunia* there is both a gene that possesses a relatively similar sequence, called *PhDEF* and there is also an atypical B function gene called PhTM6.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic studies have placed the first three within the «euAP3» lineage, while PhTM6 belongs to that of «paleoAP3».
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] As discussed above, the floral organs of eudicotyledonous angiosperms are arranged in 4 different verticils, containing the sepals, petals, stamen and carpels.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model states that the identity of these organs is determined by the homeotic genes A, A+B, B+C and C, respectively.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In contrast with the sepal and petal verticils of the eudicots, the perigone of many plants of the family Liliaceae have two nearly identical external petaloid verticils (the tepals).
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In order to explain the floral morphology of the Liliaceae, van Tunen *et al.* proposed a modified ABC model in 1993.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This model suggests that class B genes are not only expressed in verticils 2 and 3, but also in 1.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] It therefore follows that the organs of verticils 1 and 2 express class A and B genes and this is how they have a petaloid structure.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] This theoretical model has been experimentally proven through the cloning and characterization of homologs of the *Antirrhinum* genes *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* in a Liliaceae, the tulip *Tulipa gesneriana*.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are expressed in verticils 1,2 and 3.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* have also been isolated and characterized in *Agapanthus praecox* ssp.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] *orientalis* (Agapanthaceae), which is phylogenetically distant from the model organisms.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this study the genes were called *ApGLO* and *ApDEF*, respectively.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both contain open reading frames that code for proteins with 210 to 214 amino acids.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic analysis of these sequences indicated that they belong to B gene family of the monocotyledons.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In situ hybridization studies revealed that both sequences are expressed in verticil 1 as well as in 2 and 3.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] When taken together, these observations show that the floral development mechanism of *Agapanthus* also follows the modified ABC model.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, the C function is derived from one MADS-box type gene called *AGAMOUS* (*AG*), which intervenes both in the establishment of stamen and carpel identity as well as in the determination of the floral meristem.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Therefore, the *AG* mutants are devoid of androecium and gynoecium and they have petals and sepals in their place.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition, the growth in the centre of the flower is undifferentiated, therefore the petals and sepals grow in repetitive verticils.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *PLENA* (*PLE*) gene is present in *A. majus*, in place of the *AG* gene, although it is not an ortholog.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, the *FARINELLI* (*FAR*) gene is an ortholog, which is specific to the development of the anthers and the maturation of pollen.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Petunia*, *Antirrhinum* and in maize the C function is controlled by a number of genes that act in the same manner.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The genes that are closer homologs of *AG* in *Petunia* are *pMADS3* and *floral-binding protein 6* (*FBP6*).
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The D function genes were discovered in 1995.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are MADS-box proteins and they have a function that is distinct from those previously described, although they have a certain homology with C function genes.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are called *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN7* (*FBP7*) and *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN1L* (*FBP1l*).
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was found that, in *Petunia*, they are involved in the development of the ovule.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] Equivalent genes were later found in *Arabidopsis*, where they are also involved in controlling the development of carpels and the ovule and even with structures related to seed dispersal.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The appearance of interesting phenotypes in RNA interference studies in *Petunia* and tomato led, in 1994, to the definition of a new type of function in the floral development model.
[src:flowering-plant/abc-model-of-flower-development] The E function was initially thought to be only involved in the development of the three innermost verticils, however, subsequent work found that its expression was required in all the floral verticils.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] The **APG II system** (**Angiosperm Phylogeny Group II system**) of plant classification is the second, now obsolete, version of a modern, mostly molecular-based, system of plant taxonomy that was published in April 2003 by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] It was a revision of the first APG system, published in 1998, and was superseded in 2009 by a further revision, the APG III system.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] Each of the APG systems represents the broad consensus of a number of systematic botanists, united in the APG, working at several institutions worldwide.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] The APG II system recognized 45 orders, five more than the APG system.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] The new orders were Austrobaileyales, Canellales, Gunnerales, Celastrales, and Crossosomatales, all of which were families unplaced as to order, although contained in supra-ordinal clades, in the APG system.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] APG II recognized 457 families, five fewer than the APG system.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] Thirty-nine of the APG II families were not placed in any order, but 36 of the 39 were placed in a supra-ordinal clade within the angiosperms.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] Fifty-five of the families came to be known as "bracketed families".
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] They were optional segregates of families that could be circumscribed in a larger sense.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] The APG II system was influential and was adopted in whole or in part (sometimes with modifications) in a number of references.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] It was superseded 6½ years later by the APG III system, published in October 2009.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] Shown below is the classification in full detail, except for the fifteen genera and three families that were unplaced in APG II.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] The unplaced taxa were listed at the end of the appendix in a section entitled "Taxa of Uncertain Position".
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] Under some of the clades are listed the families that were placed incertae sedis in that clade.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] This means that their relationship to other members of the clade is not known.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-ii-system] Note: "+ ..." = optionally separate family, that may be split off from the preceding family.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The **APG III system** of flowering plant classification is the third version of a modern, mostly molecular-based, system of plant taxonomy being developed by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group (APG).
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] Published in 2009, it was superseded in 2016 by a further revision, the APG IV system.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The APG III system recognized all of the 45 orders of the previous system, as well as 14 new ones.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The order Ceratophyllales was erroneously marked as a new order, as it had been recognized in both of the previous APG systems.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The designation of alternative "bracketed families" was abandoned in APG III, because its inclusion in the previous system had been unpopular.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] APG III recognized 413 families, 43 fewer than in the previous system.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] Forty-four of the 55 "bracketed families" were discontinued, and 20 other families were discontinued as well.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] 21 families were accepted in the APG III system which had not been in the previous system, and a few families were moved to a different position.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The number of families not placed in any order was reduced from 39 to 10.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] Apodanthaceae and Cynomoriaceae were placed among the angiosperms, incertae sedis, that is, not in any group within the angiosperms.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] Eight other families were placed incertae sedis in various supra-ordinal groups within the angiosperms.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The paragraph below shows the number of families in each order and the placement of those families that were not included in any order.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] These figures were produced by simply counting the families in the text of the paper that established APG III.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] SUPRA-ORDINAL GROUPS: commelinids (1), basal eudicots (1), Pentapetalae (1), lamiids incertae sedis (3), core lamiids (2), angiosperms incertae sedis (2).
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The circumscription of the family Icacinaceae remains especially doubtful.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] *Apodytes* and its close relative, Rhaphiostylis, as well as *Emmotum*, *Cassinopsis*, and a few other genera were provisionally retained within it until further studies can determine whether they properly belong there.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] Three genera (*Gumillea*, *Nicobariodendron*, and *Petenaea*) were placed within the angiosperms incertae sedis.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] *Nicobariodendron* and *Petenaea* were newly added to the list.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The classification is shown below in two versions.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The short version goes to the level of orders and of families unplaced in an order.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The detailed version shows all the families.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] Orders at the same level in the classification are arranged alphabetically.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] Note that orders may not contain the same families as in earlier versions of the APG system (APG system, APG II system).
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] Further detail on relationships can be seen in the phylogenetic tree below.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The APG III system was based on a phylogenetic tree for the angiosperms which included all of the 59 orders and 4 of the unplaced families.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The systematic positions of the other 6 unplaced families was so uncertain that they could not be placed in any of the polytomies in the tree.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] They are shown in the classification table entitled "Detailed version" above, 4 in Euasterids I and 2 in Taxa of uncertain position.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] The phylogenetic tree shown below was published with the APG III system, but without some of the labels that are added here.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iii-system] A number of subfamilies have been proposed to replace some of the families which were optional (i.e. bracketed) in APG II, but have been discontinued in APG III.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iv-system] The **APG IV system** of flowering plant classification is the fourth version of a modern, mostly molecular-based, system of plant taxonomy for flowering plants (angiosperms) being developed by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group (APG).
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iv-system] It was published in 2016, seven years after its predecessor the APG III system was published in 2009, and 18 years after the first APG system was published in 1998.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iv-system] In 2009, a linear arrangement of the system was published separately; the APG IV paper includes such an arrangement, cross-referenced to the 2009 one.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iv-system] Compared to the APG III system, the APG IV system recognizes five new orders (Boraginales, Dilleniales, Icacinales, Metteniusales and Vahliales), along with some new families, making a total of 64 angiosperm orders and 416 families.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iv-system] In general, the authors describe their philosophy as "conservative", based on making changes from APG III only where "a well-supported need" has been demonstrated.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iv-system] This has sometimes resulted in placements that are not compatible with published studies, but where further research is needed before the classification can be changed.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-iv-system] Like the earlier APG systems, the APG IV revision is based on a phylogenetic tree for the angiosperms, as shown below.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-system] The **APG system** (**Angiosperm Phylogeny Group system**) of plant classification is the first version of a modern, mostly molecular-based, system of plant taxonomy.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-system] Published in 1998 by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group, it was replaced by the improved APG II in 2003, APG III system in 2009 and APG IV system in 2016.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-system] The original APG system is unusual in being based, not on total evidence, but on the cladistic analysis of the DNA sequences of three genes, two chloroplast genes and one gene coding for ribosomes.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-system] Although based on molecular evidence only, its constituent groups prove to be supported by other evidence as well, for example pollen morphology supports the split between the eudicots and the rest of the former dicotyledons.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-system] The system is rather controversial in its decisions at the family level, splitting a number of long-established families and submerging some other families.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-system] It also is unusual in not using botanical names above the level of order, that is, an order is the highest rank that will have a formal botanical name in this system.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-system] Higher groups are defined only as clades, with names such as monocots, eudicots, rosids, asterids.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-system] The APG system was superseded in 2003 by a revision, the APG II system, in 2009 by a next revision, the APG III system, and then in 2016 by a further revision, the APG IV system.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-system] The APG system recognises 462 families and 40 orders: these are assigned as follows.
[src:flowering-plant/apg-system] Note: "+ ..." = optional seggregrate family, that may be split off from the preceding family.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Angiosperms are by far the most diverse group of land plants with 64 orders, 416 families, approximately 13,000 known genera and 300,000 known species.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] They include all forbs (flowering plants without a woody stem), grasses and grass-like plants, a vast majority of broad-leaved trees, shrubs and vines, and most aquatic plants.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Angiosperms are distinguished from the other major seed plant clade, the gymnosperms, by having flowers, xylem consisting of vessel elements instead of tracheids, endosperm within their seeds, and fruits that completely envelop the seeds.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The ancestors of flowering plants diverged from the common ancestor of all living gymnosperms before the end of the Carboniferous, over 300 million years ago.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] In the Cretaceous, angiosperms diversified explosively, becoming the dominant group of plants across the planet.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Agriculture is almost entirely dependent on angiosperms, and a small number of flowering plant families supply nearly all plant-based food and livestock feed.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Rice, maize and wheat provide half of the world's staple calorie intake, and all three plants are cereals from the Poaceae family (colloquially known as grasses).
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Other families provide important industrial plant products such as wood, paper and cotton, and supply numerous ingredients for drinks, sugar production, traditional medicine and modern pharmaceuticals.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Flowering plants are commonly grown for decorative purposes, with certain flowers playing significant cultural roles in many societies.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Many flowering plants are threatened by habitat destruction and by climate change.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Angiosperms are terrestrial vascular plants; like the gymnosperms, they have roots, stems, leaves, and seeds.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] They differ from other seed plants in several ways.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The largest angiosperms are *Eucalyptus* gum trees of Australia, and *Shorea faguetiana*, dipterocarp rainforest trees of Southeast Asia, both of which can reach almost 100 metres (330 ft) in height.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The smallest are *Wolffia* duckweeds which float on freshwater, each plant less than 2 millimetres (0.08 in) across.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Considering their method of obtaining energy, some 99% of flowering plants are photosynthetic autotrophs, deriving their energy from sunlight and using it to create molecules such as sugars.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The remainder are parasitic, whether on fungi (myco-heterotrophic, formerly thought to be saprophytic) like the orchids for part or all of their life-cycle, or on other plants, either wholly like the broomrapes, *Orobanche*, or partially like the witchweeds, *Striga*.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] In terms of their environment, flowering plants are cosmopolitan, occupying a wide range of habitats on land, in fresh water and in the sea.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] On land, they are the dominant plant group in every habitat except for frigid moss-lichen tundra and coniferous forest.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The seagrasses in the Alismatales grow in marine environments, spreading with rhizomes that grow through the mud in sheltered coastal waters.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Some specialised angiosperms are able to flourish in extremely acid or alkaline habitats.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The sundews, many of which live in nutrient-poor acid bogs, are carnivorous plants, able to derive nutrients such as nitrate from the bodies of trapped insects.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Other flowers such as *Gentiana verna*, the spring gentian, are adapted to the alkaline conditions found on calcium-rich chalk and limestone, which give rise to often dry topographies such as limestone pavement.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] As for their growth habit, the flowering plants range from small, soft herbaceous plants, often living as annuals or biennials that set seed and die after one or two growing seasons, to large perennial woody trees that may live for many centuries and grow to many metres in height.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Some species grow tall without being self-supporting like trees by climbing on other plants in the manner of vines or lianas.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The number of species of flowering plants is estimated to be in the range of 250,000 to 400,000.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] This compares to around 12,000 species of moss and 11,000 species of pteridophytes.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The APG system seeks to determine the number of families, mostly by molecular phylogenetics.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] In the 2009 APG III there were 415 families.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The 2016 APG IV added five new orders (Boraginales, Dilleniales, Icacinales, Metteniusales and Vahliales), along with some new families, for a total of 64 angiosperm orders and 416 families.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The diversity of flowering plants is not evenly distributed.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Nearly all species belong to the eudicot (75%), monocot (23%), and magnoliid (2%) clades.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The remaining five clades contain a little over 250 species in total; i.e. less than 0.1% of flowering plant diversity, divided among nine families.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The botanical term "angiosperm", from Greek words *angeíon* (ἀγγεῖον 'bottle, vessel') and *spérma* (σπέρμα 'seed'), was coined in the form "Angiospermae" by Paul Hermann in 1690, including only flowering plants whose seeds were enclosed in capsules.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The term angiosperm fundamentally changed in meaning in 1827 with Robert Brown, when angiosperm came to mean a seed plant with enclosed ovules.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] In 1851, with Wilhelm Hofmeister's work on embryo-sacs, Angiosperm came to have its modern meaning of all the flowering plants including Dicotyledons and Monocotyledons.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] From 1998, the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group (APG) has reclassified the angiosperms, with updates in the APG II system in 2003, the APG III system in 2009, and the APG IV system in 2016.The APG system treats the flowering plants as an unranked clade without a formal Latin name (angiosperms).
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] A formal classification was published alongside the 2009 revision in which the flowering plants rank as the subclass Magnoliidae.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The evolutionary success and rapid diversification of angiosperms are largely attributed to their coevolutionary relationships with animal pollinators, particularly insects, birds, and bats.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Unlike gymnosperms, which rely primarily on wind for pollen dispersal, flowering plants developed specialized traits—such as nectar production, vivid pigmentations, and complex volatile scents—to attract specific floral visitors.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] This mutualism often leads to **pollination syndromes**, where the morphology of a flower evolves to match the anatomy and sensory capabilities of its primary pollinator.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Zuntini and colleagues constructed a tree of some 6,000 flowering plant genera, representing some 60% of the existing genera, on the basis of analysis of 353 nuclear genes in each specimen.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Much of the existing phylogeny is confirmed; the rosid phylogeny is revised.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Fossilised spores suggest that land plants (embryophytes) have existed for at least 475 million years.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] However, angiosperms appeared suddenly and rapidly diversified during the Early Cretaceous (beginning ~130 mya), much later than other major plant groups.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Claimed records of flowering plants prior to this are not widely accepted, as all supposed pre-Cretaceous "flowers" can be explained through being misidentifications of other seed plants.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Furthermore, almost all of these controversial fossils are described in papers co-authored by the researcher Xin Wang, such as the particularly debated *Nanjinganthus*.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Molecular evidence suggests that the ancestors of angiosperms diverged from the gymnosperms during the late Devonian to early Carboniferous, around 371-338 million years ago.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The origin time of the crown group of flowering plants remains contentious.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] By the Late Cretaceous, angiosperms appear to have dominated environments formerly occupied by ferns and gymnosperms.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Large canopy-forming trees replaced conifers as the dominant trees close to the end of the Cretaceous, 66 million years ago.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The radiation of herbaceous angiosperms occurred much later.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Fossils from the Dakota Formation in Kansas suggest that Beetles had already developed a symbiotic relationship with flowering plants such as *Archaeanthus* by the late-Albian.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The characteristic feature of angiosperms is the flower.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Its function is to ensure fertilization of the ovule and development of fruit containing seeds.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] It may arise terminally on a shoot or from the axil of a leaf.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The flower-bearing part of the plant is usually sharply distinguished from the leaf-bearing part, and forms a branch-system called an inflorescence.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Flowers produce two kinds of reproductive cells.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Microspores, which divide to become pollen grains, are the male cells; they are borne in the stamens.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The female cells, megaspores, divide to become the egg cell.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] They are contained in the ovule and enclosed in the carpel; one or more carpels form the pistil.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The flower may consist only of these parts, as in wind-pollinated plants like the willow, where each flower comprises only a few stamens or two carpels.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] In insect- or bird-pollinated plants, other structures protect the sporophylls and attract pollinators.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The individual members of these surrounding structures are known as sepals and petals (or tepals in flowers such as *Magnolia* where sepals and petals are not distinguishable from each other).
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The outer series (calyx of sepals) is usually green and leaf-like, and functions to protect the rest of the flower, especially the bud.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The inner series (corolla of petals) is, in general, white or brightly colored, is more delicate in structure, and attracts pollinators by colour, scent, and nectar.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Most flowers are hermaphroditic, producing both pollen and ovules in the same flower, but some use other devices to reduce self-fertilization.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Heteromorphic flowers have carpels and stamens of differing lengths, so animal pollinators cannot easily transfer pollen between them.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Homomorphic flowers may use a biochemical self-incompatibility to discriminate between self and non-self pollen grains.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Dioecious plants such as holly have male and female flowers on separate plants.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Monoecious plants have separate male and female flowers on the same plant; these are often wind-pollinated, as in maize, but include some insect-pollinated plants such as *Cucurbita* squashes.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Double fertilization requires two sperm cells to fertilise cells in the ovule.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] A pollen grain sticks to the stigma at the top of the pistil, germinates, and grows a long pollen tube.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] A haploid generative cell travels down the tube behind the tube nucleus.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The generative cell divides by mitosis to produce two haploid (*n*) sperm cells.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The pollen tube grows from the stigma, down the style and into the ovary.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] When it reaches the micropyle of the ovule, it digests its way into one of the synergids, releasing its contents including the sperm cells.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The synergid that the cells were released into degenerates; one sperm makes its way to fertilise the egg cell, producing a diploid (2*n*) zygote.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The second sperm cell fuses with both central cell nuclei, producing a triploid (3*n*) cell.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The zygote develops into an embryo; the triploid cell develops into the endosperm, the embryo's food supply.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The ovary develops into a fruit and each ovule into a seed.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] As the embryo and endosperm develop, the wall of the embryo sac enlarges and combines with the nucellus and integument to form the *seed coat*.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The ovary wall develops to form the fruit or pericarp, whose form is closely associated with type of seed dispersal system.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Other parts of the flower often contribute to forming the fruit.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] For example, in the apple, the hypanthium forms the edible flesh, surrounding the ovaries which form the tough cases around the seeds.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Apomixis, setting seed without fertilization, is found naturally in about 2.2% of angiosperm genera.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Some angiosperms, including many citrus varieties, are able to produce fruits through a type of apomixis called nucellar embryony.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Sexual selection is a mechanism of evolution in which members of one sex choose mates of the other sex (inter-sexual selection), and compete with members of the same sex for access to members of the opposite sex (intra-sexual selection).
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] It is an accepted concept in zoology, but more controversial in botany.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] These two mechanisms are, in theory, the main driving forces of sexual selection in flowering plants and their potential relevance to botany is clear, but more complicated than in zoology.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The complexity of applying the concept of sexual selection to plants arises from the facts that most plants are hermaphrodites and are non-sentient, meaning that the more obvious elements of female choice (e.g. aesthetic judgements on male secondary sexual characteristics) do not apply.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The research challenge currently facing botanists is mainly empirical, namely how significant these processes have actually been in plant evolution.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The masking effect is known as genetic complementation.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Meiosis in flowering plants provides a direct mechanism for repairing DNA through genetic recombination in reproductive tissues.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Sexual reproduction appears to be required for maintaining long-term genomic integrity and only infrequent combinations of extrinsic and intrinsic factors permit shifts to asexuality.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Thus the two fundamental aspects of sexual reproduction in flowering plants, cross-fertilization (outcrossing) and meiosis appear to be maintained respectively by the advantages of genetic complementation and recombinational repair.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Agriculture is almost entirely dependent on angiosperms, which provide virtually all plant-based food and fodder for livestock.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Much of this food derives from a small number of flowering plant families.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] For instance, half of the world's calorie intake is supplied by just three members of the grass family – wheat, rice and maize.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Flowering plants provide a diverse range of materials in the form of wood, paper, fibers such as cotton, flax, and hemp, medicines such as digoxin and opioids, and decorative and landscaping plants.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Coffee and hot chocolate are beverages from flowering plants (in the Rubiaceae and Malvaceae respectively).
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Both real and fictitious plants play a wide variety of roles in literature and film.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Flowers are the subjects of many poems by poets such as William Blake, Robert Frost, and Rabindranath Tagore.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Bird-and-flower painting (*Huaniaohua*) is a kind of Chinese painting that celebrates the beauty of flowering plants.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Flowers have been used in literature to convey meaning by authors including William Shakespeare.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Flowers are used in a variety of art forms which arrange cut or living plants, such as bonsai, ikebana, and flower arranging.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Ornamental plants have sometimes changed the course of history, as in tulipomania.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Many countries and regions have floral emblems; a survey of 70 of these found that the most popular flowering plant family for such emblems is Orchidaceae at 15.7% (11 emblems), followed by Fabaceae at 10% (7 emblems), and Asparagaceae, Asteraceae, and Rosaceae all at 5.7% (4 emblems each).
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Human impact on the environment has driven a range of species extinct and is threatening even more today.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Multiple organizations such as IUCN and Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew suggest that around 40% of plant species are threatened with extinction.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] The majority are threatened by habitat loss, but activities such as logging of wild timber trees and collection of medicinal plants, or the introduction of non-native invasive species, also play a role.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Relatively few plant diversity assessments have considered climate change, yet it is starting to impact plants as well.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] About 3% of flowering plants are very likely to be driven extinct within a century at 2 °C (3.6 °F) of global warming, and 10% at 3.2 °C (5.8 °F).
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] In worst-case scenarios, half of all tree species may be driven extinct by climate change over that timeframe.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Conservation in this context is the attempt to prevent extinction, whether *in situ* by protecting plants and their habitats in the wild, or *ex situ* in seed banks or as living plants.
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] Some 3000 botanic gardens around the world maintain living plants, including over 40% of the species known to be threatened, as an "insurance policy against extinction in the wild." The United Nations' Global Strategy for Plant Conservation asserts that "without plants, there is no life".
[src:flowering-plant/flowering-plant] It aims to "halt the continuing loss of plant diversity" throughout the world.
